Background: Our team previously made progress in enhancing search capabilities. We developed a method to accurately identify contexts relevant to search terms, encompassing the "what, when, where, and why" of a query. Concurrently, we also established a method to systematically decompose search terms into actionable components, enabling a more explainable and structured approach to data retrieval. Building on these achievements, this user story will focus on integrating these two types of search components. Our objective is to now associate the identified contexts with the broken-down search components. This integration will empower our Shopping List functionality to perform semantically and contextually aware data searches, and crucially, to independently validate the relevance and accuracy of its own search results.


The current Nature Breakdown Intent Extraction mode is overly restrictive and rejects valid, clinically relevant requests that are meta, analytical, or workflow-oriented in nature (for example, requests to extract clinical entities, classify clinical information, or summarize document content).

This user story enhances the existing Intent Extraction API prompt to accept and generate intents for general, non-patient-specific concepts that fall within the scope of clinical knowledge, while continuing to reject content that is entirely non-clinical.

The goal is to improve usability and alignment with real downstream use cases—such as document analysis, entity extraction, and clinical workflow support—without compromising clinical relevance boundaries.

